  <section class="sec">
    <div class="sl">Local Knowledge</div>
    <h2>Chirnside Park — Yarra Valley Edge, 1990s–2000s Estates, Cold Open Terrain</h2>
    <div class="local-box"><p>Chirnside Park sits on the outer eastern fringe of metropolitan Melbourne where the Yarra Valley begins to open up, positioned between Mooroolbark to the south-west and Lilydale to the north. The suburb developed primarily through the late 1980s, 1990s and early 2000s as Melbourne's eastern growth pushed into what had previously been farmland and market garden country at the Yarra Valley's edge. The housing stock is predominantly from this era — brick veneer and rendered homes in estate developments, with a generous proportion of those homes including freestanding wood heaters as a builder inclusion or early owner upgrade. Many of these heaters are now 20 to 30 years old and approaching the point where cumulative flue buildup becomes a genuine issue. Chirnside Park has an interesting microclimate. It sits on elevated open terrain above the Yarra Valley, exposed to cold southerly and easterly airflows during winter. The valley itself creates a cold air pool overnight, and Chirnside Park's elevated position above the valley floor means it avoids the worst of the ground frost, but it still experiences a significantly colder winter than the suburban areas further west. Wood fires are a regular feature of winter life here, and properties that were built with heaters in the 1990s are now well into the period where annual professional cleaning is genuinely important. We service Chirnside Park as part of our regular Yarra Valley fringe run.</p></div>
